 In TypeScript, you can use a type guard to narrow the type of a value to a specific type, even if the value could potentially have multiple types. Here's an example:
```
interface Person {
 name: string;
 age: number;
}

function getPerson(value: any): value is Person {
 return value != null && typeof value.name === 'string' && typeof value.age === 'number';
}

const myPerson = { name: 'John', age: 30 };

if (getPerson(myPerson)) {
 // TypeScript will now treat `myPerson` as a `Person`
 console.log(myPerson.name); // string
 console.log(myPerson.age); // number
}
```
In this example, the `getPerson` function is a type guard that checks if `value` has the properties `name` and `age` of type `string` and `number`, respectively. If `value` passes these checks, TypeScript will narrow the type of `value` to `Person`.

Alternatively, you can use a type assertion to explicitly tell TypeScript that you know the type of `value` even if it doesn't satisfy the type constraints. Here's an example:
```
function getPerson(value: any): Person {
 return value != null && typeof value.name === 'string' && typeof value.age === 'number';
