In this example, the `getPerson` function is a type assertion that explicitly tells TypeScript that `value` is a `Person`, even if it doesn't satisfy the type constraints.

Both of these techniques can be useful when you have a value that could potentially have multiple types, but you know in practice that it will only have one specific type. By using a type guard or type assertion, you can tell TypeScript to narrow the type of the value to the specific type you know it will have, which can help catch type errors and improve code readability.

